from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DateType
from pyspark.sql.functions import to_date
from pyspark.sql.functions import *


# Create a SparkSession
spark = SparkSession.builder \
    .appName("PySpark_Interview") \
    .getOrCreate()

# Define the schema for the DataFrame
schema = StructType([
    StructField("EmployeeID", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("Name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("Department", StringType(), True),
    StructField("Salary", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("JoiningDate", StringType(), True)  # Keep JoiningDate as StringType for now
])

# Sample data
data = [
    (1, "John", "Sales", 50000, "2022-01-10"),
    (2, "Alice", "HR", 60000, "2021-12-15"),
    (3, "Bob", "Engineering", 70000, "2022-02-20"),
    (4, "Emily", "Sales", 55000, "2022-03-05"),
    (5, "David", "HR", 62000, "2022-01-20")
]

# Create DataFrame
df = spark.createDataFrame(data, schema=schema)

# Convert JoiningDate column to DateType
df = df.withColumn("JoiningDate", to_date(df["JoiningDate"], "yyyy-MM-dd"))

# Show DataFrame
df.show()

#salary>55000
df1=df.filter(df.Salary>55000)
#department salary
df2=df.groupBy(df.Department).sum(df.Salary)
#desc salary
df3=df.orderBy(df.Salary.desc()).show()
#rename 
df4=df.withColumnRenamed("Salary","TOTAL_SALARY").show()
#upper name
df5=df.withColumn("Name",upper("Name")).show()
#10%bonus >60000
df6=df.withColumn("bonus",when(df["Salary"]>60000,df["Salary"]*0.1).otherwise(0)).show()
#count length of name
df7=df.withColumn("NameLength",length(df["Name"])).show()
#only year from date
df8=df.withColumn("JoiningYear",year(df["JoiningDate"])).show()
#twice the salary
df9=df.withColumn("SalaryDouble",df["Salary"]*2).show()

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.functions import monotonically_increasing_id

# Create SparkSession
spark = SparkSession.builder \
    .appName("PySpark Joins and Window Functions Demo") \
    .getOrCreate()

# Sample data for DataFrame 1
data1 = [
    (1, "Alice", "New York"),
    (2, "Bob", "Los Angeles"),
    (3, "Charlie", "Chicago"),
    (4, "David", "Houston"),
    (5, "Eve", "Philadelphia"),
    (6, "Frank", "Phoenix"),
    (7, "Grace", "San Antonio"),
    (8, "Henry", "San Diego"),
    (9, "Ivy", "Dallas"),
    (10, "Jack", "San Jose")
]

# Sample data for DataFrame 2
data2 = [
    (1, 25, "Manager"),
    (3, 30, "Analyst"),
    (5, 35, "Engineer"),
    (7, 40, "Director"),
    (9, 45, "Consultant"),
    (11, 50, "Developer"),
    (13, 55, "Architect"),
    (15, 60, "Designer"),
    (17, 65, "Coordinator"),
    (19, 70, "Administrator")
]

# Create DataFrames from sample data
df1 = spark.createDataFrame(data1, ["id", "name", "city"])
df2 = spark.createDataFrame(data2, ["id", "age", "job"])

# Inner Join: Returns only the rows with matching keys in both DataFrames.
innerjoin=df1.join(df2,'id','inner')
innerjoin.show()
# Left Join: Returns all rows from the left DataFrame and matching rows from the right DataFrame.
left_outer=df1.join(df2,'id','leftouter')
left_outer.show()
# Right Join: Returns all rows from the right DataFrame and matching rows from the left DataFrame.
right_outer=df1.join(df2,'id','rightouter')
right_outer.show()
# Full Outer Join: Returns all rows from both DataFrames, including matching and non-matching rows.

fullouter=df1.join(df2,'id','fullouter')
fullouter.show()
# Left Semi Join: Returns all rows from the left DataFrame where there is a match in the right DataFrame.
leftsemi=df1.join(df2,'id','semi')
leftsemi.show()
# Left Anti Join: Returns all rows from the left DataFrame where there is no match in the right DataFrame.

antijoin=df1.join(df2,'id','anti')
antijoin.show()

from pyspark.sql.window import Window
from pyspark.sql.functions import row_number, rank, dense_rank, cume_dist

# Window specification
window_spec = Window.orderBy("id")

# Row number
row_number_df = df1.withColumn("row_number", row_number().over(window_spec))
row_number_df.show()
# Rank
rank_df = df1.withColumn("rank", rank().over(window_spec))
rank_df.show()
# Dense rank
dense_rank_df = df1.withColumn("dense_rank", dense_rank().over(window_spec))
dense_rank_df.show()
# Cumulative distribution
cume_dist_df = df1.withColumn("cume_dist", cume_dist().over(window_spec))
cume_dist_df.show()
